Israel's FMD follow-up report No. 11
------------------------------------
Information received on (and dated) 1 Apr 2007 from Dr Michel
Bellaiche, Epidemiologist, Veterinary Services and Animal Health,
Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Development, Beit Dagan, Israel
Summary
Report type: follow-up report No. 11
Date of start of event: 28 Dec 2006
Date of confirmation of event: 1 Apr 2007
Report date: 1 Apr 2007
Date submitted to OIE: 2 Apr 2007
Reason for notification: reoccurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence: December 2005
Manifestation of disease: clinical disease
Causal agent: FMD virus, serotype O1
Nature of diagnosis: clinical, laboratory (basic), laboratory (advanced)
Report pertains to: entire country
New outbreaks
Summary of outbreaks
Total outbreaks: 1
Outbreak location: Hura village, District: Hadarom ("South")
Affected animals
Species: sheep/goats
Susceptible: 100
Cases: 2
Deaths: 0
Destroyed: 0
Slaughtered: 0
Epidemiology
Source of infection: fomites (humans, vehicles, feed, etc.); airborne spread.
Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type: National FMD Laboratory, Kimron Veterinary
Institute (National laboratory)
Test: pathogen isolation on cell culture.
Test date: 1 Apr 2007
Result: positive
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[For the full notification and a map showing the location of Hura,
subscribers are referred to the source URL above.
It may be assumed that the given number of 2 cases out of 100
susceptible animals stands for clearly clinically affected animals,
others probably subclinically affected, a known phenomenon in adult
small ruminants.
A summary of the Israeli epizootic since its start on 28 Dec 2006,
including a map showing all 22 outbreaks recorded so far and links to
the initial immediate notification and the 10 previous follow-up
reports, is available at
<http://www.oie.int/wahid-prod/public.php?page=event_summary&this_country_code=ISR&public_disease=1&reportid=4351>.
The recent spread of the disease into southern Israel seems to be
related to its distribution in the southern part (Hebron area) of the
West Bank (see item 2, below). This will be clearly demonstrable when
one looks at the 2 summarising WAHID maps, referred to in the 2
reports. - Mod.AS]
