Palestinian Autonomous Territories: FMD follow-up report No. 3
--------------------------------------------------------------
Information received on (and dated) 3 Apr 2007 from Dr Imad Mukarker,
Deputy Director General , Veterinary Services and Animal Health,
Ministry of Agriculture , Naplouse, Palestinian Auton. Territories
Summary
Report type: follow-up report No. 3
Date of start of event: 2 Feb 2007
Date of confirmation of event: 8 Feb 2007
Report date: 3 Apr 2007
Date submitted to OIE: 4 Apr 2007
Reason for notification: reoccurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence: 20 Jun 2006
Manifestation of disease: clinical disease
Causal agent: FMD virus, serotype O
Nature of diagnosis: suspicion, clinical, laboratory (basic),
laboratory (advanced), necropsy
Report pertains to: entire country
New outbreaks
Outbreak 1: Bzaria, Tulkarem, West Bank
Date of start of outbreak: 7 Mar 2007
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not submitted)
Epidemiological unit: village
Affected animals
Species: sheep/goats
Susceptible: 100
Cases: 8
Deaths: 2
Destroyed: 0
Slaughtered: 0
Affected population: only young kids less than 30 days old showed
clinical signs. Adult sheep did not show clinical signs, except for
lameness, which lasted 2 days.
Outbreak 2: Beir Zeit, Ramallah, West Bank
Date of start of outbreak: 14 Mar 2007
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not submitted)
Epidemiological unit: farm
Affected animals
Species: sheep
Susceptible: 200
Cases: 6
Deaths: 4
Destroyed: 0
Slaughtered: 0
Affected population: only young kids less than 30 days old showed
clinical signs. Adult sheep did not show clinical signs, except for
lameness, which lasted 2 days.
Outbreak 3: Tarameh, Durah, West Bank
Date of start of outbreak: 7 Mar 2007
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not submitted)
Epidemiological unit: village
Affected animals
Species: goats
Susceptible: 75
Cases: 41
Deaths: 23
Destroyed:0
Slaughtered:0
Affected population: only young kids less than 30 days old showed
clinical signs. Adult sheep did not show clinical signs, except for
