Susceptible: 150
Cases: 9
Deaths: 3
Destroyed: 0
Slaughtered: 0
Affected population: only young kids less than 30 days old showed
clinical signs. Adult sheep did not show clinical signs, except for
lameness, which lasted 2 days.
Outbreak 6: Jabah, Jerusalem, West Bank
Date of start of outbreak: 5 Mar 2007
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not submitted)
Epidemiological unit: village
Affected animals
Species: sheep/goats
Susceptible: 500
Cases: 10
Deaths: 5
Destroyed: 0
Slaughtered: 0
Affected population: fattening animals. Only young kids less than 30
days old showed clinical signs. Adult sheep did not show clinical
signs, except for lameness, which lasted 2 days.
Outbreak 7: Ramallah, Ramallah, West Bank
Date of start of outbreak: 4 Mar 2007
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not submitted)
Epidemiological unit: farm
Affected animals
Species: sheep/goats
Susceptible: 35
Cases: 11
Deaths: 5
Destroyed: 0
Slaughtered: 0
Affected population: only young kids less than 30 days old showed
clinical signs. Adult sheep did not show clinical signs, except for
lameness, which lasted 2 days.
Summary of outbreaks
Total outbreaks: 7
Total animals affected
Species: sheep/goats
Susceptible: 635
Cases: 29
Deaths: 12
Destroyed: 0
Slaughtered: 0
Species: sheep
Susceptible: 567
Cases: 30
deaths: 22
Destroyed: 0
Slaughtered: 0
Species: goats
Susceptible: 75
Cases: 41
Deaths: 23
Destroyed: 0
Slaughtered: 0
Outbreak statistics [see commentary]
Species: sheep/goats
Apparent morbidity rate: 4.57 percent
Apparent mortality rate: 1.89 percent
Apparent case fatality rate: 41.38 percent
Proportion susceptible removed*: 1.89 percent
Sheep
Apparent morbidity rate: 5.29 percent
Apparent mortality rate: 3.88 percent
Apparent case fatality rate: 73.33 percent
Proportion susceptible removed*: 3.88 percent
Goats
Apparent morbidity rate: 54.67 percent
Apparent mortality rate: 30.67 percent
Apparent case fatality rate: 56.10 percent
Proportion susceptible removed*: 30.67 percent
* Removed from the susceptible population either through death,
destruction, or slaughter
Epidemiology
Source of infection:
-introduction of new live animals
-illegal movement of animals
-contact with infected animal(s) at grazing/watering
Epidemiological comments
The post-mortem examination of young animals revealed typical lesions
of "tiger heart". A very high mortality among lambs and kids aged
less than 2 years was observed.
A mass vaccination was applied in all districts of the West Bank. The
total amount of vaccinated animals is 350 000. Vaccination is ongoing.
Control measures
Measures already applied
-movement control inside the country
-vaccination in response to the outbreak (s)
-disinfection of infected premises/establishment(s)
-quarantine
-vaccination permitted
-treatment of affected animals (symptomatic treatment and
oxy-tetracycline injection)
Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type: Beit-Dagan laboratory (Local laboratory)
Test: polymerase chain reaction (PCR)
Test date: 22 Mar 2007
Result: positive
Test: enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay (ELISA)
Test date: 22 Mar 2007
Result: Positive
Test: pathogen isolation on cell culture.
Test date: 16 Mar 2007
Result: positive
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[For the original notification, including a map showing the 7 new
outbreaks, subscribers are referred to the source URL above. Two of
the outbreaks are situated in the southern part of the West Bank
(Outbreak 3 in Tarameh, Durah, and outbreak 4 in Zahret Nada,
Bethlehem); see commentary to the item on FMD in Israel.
The given outbreak statistics demonstrate a significantly higher
mortality rate in the susceptible goat population, compared to sheep.
This is mainly due to the fact that the timing of parturition of
goats in the affected region (Israel and Palestinian Authority (PAT),
as well as Jordan) is, generally, one to 2 months later than in
sheep. Hence, in goat flocks affected in March [2007], the proportion
of young, susceptible offspring is higher than in sheep flocks,
leading to the observed higher mortality rate.
A summary of the PAT epizootic since its reported start on 2 Feb
2007, including a map showing all 17 outbreaks recorded so far and
links to the initial immediate notification and the 2 previous
follow-up reports, is available at
<http://www.oie.int/wahid-prod/public.php?page=event_summary&this_country_code=PSE&public_disease=1&reportid=4851>.
- Mod.AS]
